##As Japan's epidemic spreads, will the Tokyo Olympics be held as scheduled?

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. Whether this year's Olympic torch relay, which is scheduled to start in Greece on March 12, arrive in Japan on March 26 and begin in Tokyo on July 24, will be affected depends on the Japanese government's efforts to contain the outbreak

Tokyo Olympic Torch Relay Ambassador Satomi Ishihara (right) shakes hands with the temporary "torch bearer" during a rehearsal in Tokyo February 15,2020. By Wang Xiaofeng, CAIJING correspondent

Editor | Hao Zhou

Will the new crown epidemic affect the Tokyo Olympics? "I think so, " Masahiro Kami, Director of the nonprofit organization, told Caijing in an interview. Shang is deeply concerned about the rapid spread of NCP in Japan. He has published articles in several well-known Japanese media, including weekly Wenchun and weekly Xinchao, criticizing the current response of the Japanese government.

"Most Japanese people are looking forward to the Olympics, but it's difficult to hold them as planned. Most countries, except Japan, are hesitant to participate in the Tokyo Olympics, " Shang said gloomily.

As of the evening of February 21 local time, including the "Diamond Princess" cruise ship infection, including the number of people, a total of 737 confirmed cases of new coronavirus infection in Japan, three deaths. As of February 20,634 people had been diagnosed on the diamond princess, the largest cluster of infections outside mainland China. One of the passengers, an 87-year-old man from Kanagawa Prefecture and an 84-year-old woman from Tokyo, who were confirmed to have contracted the new coronavirus, died after being taken to a medical facility.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"London wants to take over the Olympics. "

The Tokyo Games were scheduled to begin on July 24, and Japan was scheduled to run a series of test events early this year to ensure the venues and camps were functioning properly. Although there have been sporadic cases of new coronavirus infection, this has not affected Tokyo's preparations. However, the diamond princess incident changed the course of events.

Given the rapid pace of the outbreak, Japan has scaled back two important marathons, in Tokyo and Nagoya, and cancelled some smaller city marathons. The Tokyo Paralympic Games'Bocce test, scheduled for next week, has been cancelled, the first Olympic and Paralympic test event to be affected by the outbreak.

As international concern mounted, the London Conservatives mayoral candidate Sean Bailey even said London would take over the Games from Tokyo if the new crown disease forced a change of venue, to host this sporting event.

The development of the epidemic has caused great distress to the Tokyo Olympic Organizing Committee, the Japanese government and the Tokyo City government. In the face of concerns, the International Olympic Committee and Japanese authorities have repeatedly stressed in recent weeks that they are not prepared to cancel or postpone the Tokyo Olympics. Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshihide Suga stressed at a press conference on February 21 that the Tokyo Olympic and Paralympic Games would be held as scheduled. Seiko Hashimoto, Japan's Olympic Minister, also said the flame, which starts on March 26, would continue as normal.

Japan is stepping up preparations, from late February to April will still be held a series of contest testing activities, for the race to accumulate virus control experience. Masa Takaya, a spokesman for the Tokyo Olympics, said five "no's" when asked whether Japan would postpone or cancel the tests. The first phase of the test, which will take place this month, is limited to Japanese athletes, he said. The second phase of testing is planned for March and April and will include wheelchair football and gymnastics. He stressed that some testing activities would be fine-tuned, but they would certainly be done.

Responding to the pressure of the outbreak, the World Health Organization (WHO) called for calm, and spokesman Tariq Jasarevic said there was no evidence of community infection outside China, so the WHO is not calling for the cancellation of large gatherings at this time.

Marion is a member of the WHO's emergency committee. Kupmans was one of 16 experts present at a meeting of the WHO's emergency committee at its headquarters in Geneva on January 22 to discuss whether the new pneumonia outbreak constitutes a "public health emergency of international concern. ".

As to whether the outbreak will endanger the Tokyo Olympics, Kupmans told Caijing that although she has been quoted in the media suggesting that the Games are dangerous, this is not the case. We need to wait and see if the virus is controlled through prevention and control measures in China and other countries and regions.

"In the long run, if [ these measures ] do not succeed, we are likely to see wider dissemination in other parts of the world. Whether this leads to measures such as travel restrictions will depend on how severe it is. When we look at the data from China, we do see the severity of the disease, but we also know that the majority of cases [ of symptoms ] are mild and we can only speculate about the exact course of recent events,"Kupmans said.

No Olympic Games in history have been cancelled or postponed for reasons other than war.

People in the insurance industry believe that infectious diseases will be part of Tokyo's insurance policy for the 2020 Olympics. Olympic organizers typically insure against losses on ticket sales, and the International Olympic Committee takes out additional insurance to cover potential losses on sponsors and broadcast revenue. As a general rule, infectious diseases are not excluded from coverage for the Olympics, according to a leading underwriter at Lloyd's of London.

So, in theory, if the Tokyo Olympics were cancelled because of new pneumonia, the terms would be activated. In the case of premiums, Lloyd's estimates suggest that the payments may amount to between 1.5 and 3 per cent of the coverage. Given that the Tokyo 2020 organizers say the budget is # 9.7 bn, assuming premiums are 3 per cent of the amount insured, the cost of insuring would be # 291m.

The ANBE administration faces a crisis of confidence

As well as casting a shadow over the Tokyo Olympics, the ANBE administration faces a huge crisis of confidence, with approval ratings for the Anbe administration dropping as low as 38 percent. When asked about the government's response to new pneumonia in a national poll conducted by the Asahi Shimbun Company on February 15-16,50 percent of respondents said "no good" and only 34 percent said "good" . Eighty-five percent of respondents said they were "very" and "somewhat" uneasy about the spread of the infection in Japan.

Forty-five percent of those surveyed said the government's handling of the diamond princess was inappropriate, causing the virus to spread. In dealing with the Diamond Princess, the Japanese government has faced internal and external pressure. Over the past two weeks, the Japanese government has been walking a tough tightrope between passenger rights and the spread of the epidemic, based on quarantine laws, passengers are required to observe their health on board for 14 days for quarantine purposes, and Japan does not allow non-quarantine personnel to disembark.

However, after several days of isolation, as conditions on the ship gradually deteriorated and the number of infected people rose rapidly, the policy of isolation was increasingly questioned, some public health experts argue that the isolation of so many passengers in such confined spaces doubles the chances of infection. Kentaro Iwata, a professor of infectious disease at Kobe University, slammed the quarantine on board as the biggest mistake, a huge mistake and a high risk of secondary infection.

Regarding the Japanese measures, Kupmans told Caijing that although he did not know the specific situation on board the Diamond Princess, according to the usual practice, quarantine can prevent further spread, so it needs to last 14 days, until the last contact with the patient or the source of the virus... but quarantine doesn't have to be on the ship, it can be at home.

Japanese officials have defended the sea quarantine, which Shigeru Omi, the former WHO's regional director for the Western Pacific, said was effective in reducing infections, most of which occurred before the quarantine began.

UEMO agrees with Shigeru Omi, whose team helped Professor Kiyoshi Ihara at the University of Tokyo's Institute of Medical Sciences to study the trajectory of H1N1 in Japan in 2009, they found that while quarantining at airport entry points helped to detect cases, the people found to be infected were only the tip of the iceberg, as there was an incubation period and subsequent statistics showed that a large number of cases had been missed at entry points, this suggests that the measure is limited, as is the case with ships.

Japan's government has also been criticized for its slow pace of quarantine, which was limited in its ability to do so, but it took several days to request the assistance of civilian agencies and did not screen all passengers until a day before the end of the quarantine. Because screening is slow, it is even more difficult to determine when an infection begins. "The Ministry of Health should work with private companies to expand virus detection capabilities, rather than relying on the already overstretched State Institute of Medical Science, " he said.

Not only that, but the Japanese government's decision to allow hundreds of passengers who tested negative after the quarantine to disembark and take public transportation home has raised concerns, it is unclear whether the passengers who tested negative were infected during the quarantine but remain in the incubation period of the virus. The US, Australia, Canada and South Korea said the evacuees would return to their countries on chartered flights for a further two weeks of isolation, some at military bases, suggesting they did not trust the quarantine measures on board.

He is not convinced that the passengers will be able to spread the virus in Japan. Because while some passengers may have been infected on board and showed no signs of infection, if handled properly, the risk of the carrier becoming infected does not appear to be high.

The government's response to the diamond princess also reflects the problems with Japan's bureaucracy. CHILLE CLEVELAND, a professor of sociology at Temple University's Tokyo campus, has studied the Japanese government's response to the Fukushima disaster. Comparing the two events, Cleveland saw disturbing similarities. In his view, this shows that Japan's Bureaucratic Crisis Management is deeply flawed, and that the lack of real experts responsible for coordinating decision making is deeply problematic because it puts government officials in positions of authority that are beyond their ability.

"Japan is sometimes a victim of its own capacity, where everything is working well and it is a highly structured and functioning society in all respects. When things go off track, they think it's enough to have a normal routine, but special circumstances call for special responses,"Cleveland said.

"Japan is a country with a lot of natural disasters, so it has a very special personality, so it doesn't seem that scary at the moment. But infectious diseases are not like earthquakes, tsunamis, typhoons and so on. I think we still need some kind of fear and vigilance. So I think Professor Iwada's warning is very meaningful,"a reporter from a well-known Japanese media in China told Caijing.

The China correspondent believes the Japanese government must control the outbreak, not be able to deal with the problem, because national lives are at stake, or the consequences will be serious. In his view, the outbreak may affect the Tokyo Olympics, "I personally think the Tokyo Olympics do not have to start on time. In order to hold the Olympics at the expense of life, also unreasonable. "

Focus on high-risk individuals

At present, the development of the epidemic in Japan is on the one hand, severe cases of death, on the other hand, the spread of infection but more mild disease. In view of this situation, the Japanese government will focus on people at higher risk of severe illness, in order to thoroughly prevent infection in high-risk groups such as the elderly, at the same time, to build a mechanism to identify patients as early as possible and give priority to treatment.

The Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare on Feb. 17 issued guidelines for people with fever and other symptoms to call a counseling center, listing symptoms of a cold and fever above 37.5 degrees for more than four days. Since the elderly and people with underlying diseases are prone to severe symptoms, such people should be consulted by telephone after 2 days or so of symptoms.

If the centre deems it necessary, the suspect will be referred to a specialized medical institution with a "out-patient Clinic for returnees and contacts" . The number of medical facilities with specialist outpatient clinics reached 726 as of February 15, and the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare is aiming to expand to about 800 as of the 2009 swine flu outbreak. The ministry has also increased the number of special beds to about 3,400. Depending on the spread of the infection, patients with severe cases may be given priority admission to hospitals, while those with mild cases may recuperate in their own homes.

Eliminating nosocomial infection is the key to preventing high-risk individuals from being infected. After the outbreak of the new pneumonia, there were many nosocomial infections in Wuhan. At home, there are also suspected cases of staff and patients infecting each other in Wakayama Prefecture and Kanagawa Prefecture. Hiro Takayama, chief of Infectious Medicine at Okinawa Central Hospital, said that if the infection had spread in a facility with 100 residents, more than 30 people would have become ill and several died.

To identify high risk patients early, the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare expanded the range of people tested for the virus beyond travel history or exposure in China, and doctors determined suspected infections. The tests, initially carried out by the Institute of Medical Science, can carry about 1,500 people a day, but are not running at full capacity because of insufficient personnel and reagents, with the assistance of enterprises and universities, the testing capacity has been increased to more than 3,000 people. As there is no new specific medicine for pneumonia at this stage, Japan has adopted such symptomatic treatment as pneumonia. The Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare funds research for clinical trials, avoiding the cost to individual patients.

The government is pushing ahead with the measures to ensure the outbreak is contained and the Tokyo Olympics are not affected. Regarding the future direction of the epidemic, uchihiro believes that Japan is unlikely to become the second center of transmission because the new coronavirus has already spread in East Asia, including South Korea, Japan and Taiwan.

The Olympic torch relay will begin in Greece on March 12 and arrive in Japan on March 26, and the impact on these iconic events will depend on the Japanese government's efforts to contain the outbreak. Every four years, from organizers to athletes, the Tokyo Games take years of effort, and as World Health Organization, the organizing expert, puts it, the course of the global epidemic will determine whether the games stay on track.
